{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"93ad89c9-44ab-4a7c-9932-424795f2e98c","content":"## What happened\n\nC# 13 introduced **first-class span** support. Arrays (`T[]`) now have an implicit conversion to `ReadOnlySpan<T>` that participates in overload resolution. This means:\n\n- **Before (.NET 9 / C# 12):** `array.Contains(num)` resolved to `Enumerable.Contains<T>(this IEnumerable<T>, T)` — works fine in expression trees.\n- **After (.NET 10 / C# 14):** `array.Contains(num)` resolves to `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(this ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` — the span overload is \"more specific\" and wins.\n\nSince `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct**, it cannot be captured in expression trees. The expression tree compiler/interpreter chokes on the span-based method call.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nForce the compiler to resolve back to `Enumerable.Contains` by disambiguating the receiver type:\n\n**Option 1 — Cast to `IEnumerable<int>`:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\n**Option 2 — Call `Enumerable.Contains` explicitly (non-extension style):**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\n**Option 3 — Use `.AsEnumerable()`:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);\n```\n\nAll three ensure the LINQ `Enumerable.Contains` overload is selected, which expression trees can represent. Option 2 is the most explicit and least likely to regress in future compiler updates.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e336345d-c174-4284-bea7-119138aa43a6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on arrays.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 / C# 14 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change: **arrays now implement `System.Linq.IEnumerable<T>` through a new generic interface hierarchy**, and more relevantly, C# 14 introduces **extension members** (extension types). But more specifically, the issue here is about how the compiler resolves `.Contains()`.\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. \n\nThe real issue is likely about overload resolution between `Enumerable.Contains` and `MemoryExtensions.Contains`. In .NET 9, calling `.Contains()` on an array resolved to the LINQ extension method, but .NET 10 probably introduced span-based overloads that now take precedence, changing which method gets called and potentially breaking expression tree compilation. But wait — `MemoryExtensions.Contains(this ReadOnlySpan<char>, char)` is for chars specifically...\n\nActually, I think the real issue is different. Let me reconsider.\n\nIn .NET 9 (C# 13), `array.Contains(value)` resolves to `Enumerable.Contains<T>()`. This works fine with expression trees because `Enumerable.Contains` is a standard static method call that expression trees can represent.\n\nIn .NET 10 / C# 14, the compiler may now resolve `array.Contains(value)` to a different overload — specifically `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(this Span<T>, T)` or `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(this ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` — because `int[]` is implicitly convertible to `Span<int>` / `ReadOnlySpan<int>`. This is the first-class Span feature that C# 13 introduced, allowing spans to participate more naturally in overload resolution, and C# 14 refined those rules further. So now `MemoryExtensions.Contains` becomes the preferred overload, but expression trees can't represent it since it's an intrinsic method. The core problem is that `array.Contains(x)` now resolves to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` with a `ReadOnlySpan<T>` parameter instead of `Enumerable.Contains`, but expression trees can't represent ref structs, so the expression tree compilation fails at runtime. If the compiler resolves `.Contains()` to `MemoryExtensions.Contains`, that should trigger a compile-time error since ref structs can't appear in expression trees—but the user says it throws at runtime, which suggests either they're describing a compile error loosely or there's something else going on. Let me look at the actual code to understand what's happening.\n\nThe most likely explanation is that C# 13 introduced a breaking change in how the compiler resolves overloads, now preferring span-based methods over the traditional `Enumerable.Contains`, and this preference is causing the runtime issue when the expression tree is interpreted. to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` instead of `Enumerable.Contains` when using .NET 10 with C# 14, which is the breaking change causing the issue. The user likely had language version constraints in .NET 9 that prevented this behavior, but upgrading to .NET 10 activated the newer resolution rules by default.\n\nThe problem stems from first-class span support—arrays now implicitly convert to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, and the span-based overload wins during overload resolution. Since expression trees can't contain ref structs, this breaks the code. The solution is to explicitly cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` or call `Enumerable.Contains` directly to force the older overload. Since `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a ref struct, it can't be used in expression trees, which causes either a compile-time error or a runtime failure when the interpreter tries to handle the span-based method. The fix is straightforward—either cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` or explicitly call `Enumerable.Contains` to force the older overload resolution.","outputTokens":3186},"id":"44a309bd-1e43-4b7c-8fc8-6162d0f89d76","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:34:42.700Z","parentId":"820212ef-f1da-4941-b193-9fbcbe8fa676"}
